Media skewing it into "two groups clashing" ruins the rhetoric of it being a fundamentally anti-government protest. And if the people are primarily targeting the political establishment/police, it becomes obvious Muslim groups involved are wielded as a paramilitary by the regime.

The media wants to portray British protests as "white nationalists against Muslims", because it's easier to "manage" the situation from above that way, the protestors were fighting the police and attacking government buildings. It is a political protest and not "random" violence.

It is obvious that when Islam is targeted it's only because it's seen as a "symbol" of the current hostile political regime in Britain. The true target the protests are aimed against is obviously the traitorous political class and the police protecting it against the people.

Liberals are happy to repeat "ACAB" or "defund the police" as slogans in peace-time, but when a popular uprising actually takes place against a political regime, they are always the first to beg the police to come and suppress it as brutally as possible to protect the government.

When it comes to day to day petty crime, it's easy to appear cool and aloof with the usual "ACAB"/"1312" graffiti, but when actual political change through revolution is possible, it all immediately reverts to "omg where are the riot cops, they are literally destroying property".

You often see it in soy types who make a little show of announcing how they'll be offline for a weekend or so on vacation, not checking their notifs or our beloved TL, but one cannot help but find it somewhat unsatisfactory, like an alcoholic's too enthusiastic newfound sobriety.

It's obvious that when people artificially restrain their access to social media, the internet (e.g. reading on the porch for an afternoon and not taking your phone so you're not tempted to check twitter) all they're doing is reinforcing a pathological relationship to technology.

Any peaty allegory to table sugar or coffee will make sense here, but the essence of it is any thing you set out this pattern of "abuse and deprivation of" over will probably result in disordered behavior in some way down the line. Outside of e.g. "programmed" Lenten fasting etc.

If you remember some solitary, lonely old person from your childhood who is long gone now, it is good to try to pray for their soul. There are many people left waiting in Hades for someone to pray them out of there before The Day of the Lord, people with no one to pray for them.

And I believe it was St. Paisios who said if we pray for those forgotten and lonely dead people, our prayers for the souls of our own close relatives who are no longer on earth will be heard even more clearly in Heaven. Salvation is communal, we all drag each other out of Hades.
